# Phase 1 — World & the Game Loop

This is the costly correctness fork. Two mistakes here silently ship broken apps that still build green: a dead game loop (per-frame logic not in an ECS System) and `(world as any)` casts that mask wrong paths. Both are covered in full depth below.

## Contents

- World Creation
- WorldOptions is typed — never blanket-cast
- Dual-Runtime Pattern (XR + Browser Fallback)
- World is fully typed — never `(world as any)`
- Per-Frame Logic = ECS Systems (the ONLY supported game loop)
- ECS-Native Player Rig

> Physics, audio, asset management, and input live in `03-subsystems.md`. CLI commands (`iwsdk ecs systems`, `scene hierarchy`) live in `cli-reference.md`. Verification (`tsc --noEmit` + screenshot) lives in `troubleshooting.md`.

## World Creation

```typescript
// XR world (default)
const world = await World.create(container);

// XR world with options
const world = await World.create(container, {
  xr: { offer: 'once' }, // or 'always' / 'none'; omit xr for the default
  render: { near: 0.01, far: 200 },
  features: {
    grabbing: true,
    locomotion: true,
    physics: true,
    spatialUI: false,
  },
});

// Browser-first world (no XR)
const world = await World.create(container, {
  xr: false,
  render: {
    near: 0.001,
    far: 200,
    camera: { position: [0, 1.6, 0], lookAt: [0, 1.55, -1] },
  },
  input: { canvasPointerEvents: true },
  features: {
    grabbing: true,
    locomotion: { browserControls: true }, // WASD/arrows + Space + gamepad; app owns mouselook
    physics: true,
  },
});
```

## WorldOptions is typed — never blanket-cast

`World.create` options are **typed** (`WorldOptions`). Do not blanket-cast the options object to `any` — a type error here means a wrong key (e.g. `render` vs a runtime member), not a framework bug.

The whole bag typechecks as-is against `@iwsdk/core`. Do NOT write `await World.create(container, { ... } as any)`: a blanket cast silently masks every later misconfig. If one key errors, fix that one key. The keys are all real and typed:

- `xr`: `false | { offer?: 'none' | 'once' | 'always', ... }`. `offer: 'once'` is a string-union literal — it needs **no** `as const` and **no** `as any`.
- `render`: `{ fov?, near?, far?, defaultLighting?, stencil?, camera? }`. `render.camera` is `{ position?, rotation?, quaternion?, lookAt? }` (all `[x,y,z]`; `quaternion` is `[x,y,z,w]`) and sets the initial local pose under `world.player`.
- `input`: `{ canvasPointerEvents? }`, type `boolean | { enabled?, activeDuringXR? }`.
- `features.locomotion`: `boolean | { ..., browserControls?, turningMethod?, enableJumping?, ... }`; `browserControls` is `boolean | { keyboard?, gamepad? }`.
- `features`: `grabbing | locomotion | physics | sceneUnderstanding | environmentRaycast | camera | spatialUI`.

The container arg is an `HTMLElement`; the common pattern is `const container = document.getElementById('scene-container') as HTMLDivElement;`.

## Dual-Runtime Pattern (XR + Browser Fallback)

For games that should work both in VR and in the browser:

```typescript
const world = await World.create(container, {
  xr: { offer: 'once' },
  input: { canvasPointerEvents: true },
  features: {
    grabbing: true,
    locomotion: { browserControls: true },
    physics: true,
  },
});
```

## World is fully typed — never `(world as any)`

These are all public, typed members of `World` (`packages/core/src/ecs/world.ts`). Casting to `any` strips autocomplete and silently masks wrong paths (e.g. `(world as any).ecs?.registerSystem?.(...)` and `(world as any).render?.camera` no-op — there is no `world.ecs` or `world.render` at runtime).

```typescript
world.scene; // Scene
world.camera; // PerspectiveCamera — the active camera in BOTH browser and XR
world.renderer; // WebGLRenderer (three)
world.input; // InputManager (see Input System below)
world.player; // XROrigin Group (player rig)
world.playerEntity; // Entity wrapping the XROrigin Group
world.cameraEntity; // Entity wrapping the camera
```

**Active camera:** use `world.camera`. It is parented to the player rig and is what the render loop passes to `renderer.render(scene, camera)`, so its world transform tracks the headset during a session. Do **not** traverse the scene graph (`scene.getObjectByProperty('isCamera', …)`, a `findCamera()` helper) or reach for `renderer.xr.getCamera()` in app code. Example — screen-pointer raycast:

```typescript
raycaster.setFromCamera(new Vector2(ndcX, ndcY), world.camera);
```

**System / component registration is chainable and typed** — call it on `world`, not a fictional `world.ecs`:

```typescript
world.registerComponent(MyComponent).registerSystem(MySystem);
```

## Per-Frame Logic = ECS Systems (the ONLY supported game loop)

`World.create` already starts the render/update loop (the XR session loop in immersive mode). Put **all** per-frame game logic in a registered `System`. Do not hand-roll `requestAnimationFrame`, do not call `renderer.setAnimationLoop`, and do not override `world.update`.

```typescript
import { createSystem, World } from '@iwsdk/core';

// queries + a config schema are both optional
export class GameLoopSystem extends createSystem({
  balls: {
    required: [
      /* components */
    ],
  },
}) {
  private game!: GameManager;

  init() {
    /* one-time setup; runs once on register */
  }

  // Inject app collaborators with a setter — the ENGINE constructs the system,
  // so you cannot pass them through a constructor.
  setRefs(refs: { game: GameManager }) {
    this.game = refs.game;
  }

  // The per-frame tick. Name MUST be `update`. Args are in SECONDS, not ms.
  update(delta: number, time: number) {
    this.game.update(delta);
    this.queries.balls.entities.forEach((e) => {
      /* ... */
    });
    if (this.input.keyboard.getKeyDown('Space')) {
      /* ... */
    }
  }
}

world.registerSystem(GameLoopSystem); // register the CLASS, not an instance
const loop = world.getSystem(GameLoopSystem)!; // typed instance back
loop.setRefs({ game });
```

Inside a system, world resources are already on `this`: `this.world`, `this.scene`, `this.camera`, `this.renderer`, `this.input`, `this.player`, `this.playerEntity`, `this.queries`, `this.config`.

**These do NOT exist — a TS error here is a real bug, never "a known IWSDK typing issue." Do not cast `world` to `any` to silence it:**

| Guessed (wrong)                                                | Reality                                                                                                                                                  |
| -------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `world.onUpdate(fn)` / `world.onFrame`                         | No such method. `World.update(delta,time)` is the engine tick the runtime calls for you — do not call, assign, or wrap it.                               |
| `world.ecs.registerSystem(...)`                                | No `world.ecs`. `(world as any).ecs?.registerSystem?.(...)` silently no-ops and ships a dead loop.                                                       |
| `world.createSystem({...})`                                    | No such method (returns `undefined`). `createSystem(...)` is the imported factory used as a base class.                                                  |
| `class { execute(dt) {} }`                                     | The tick method is `update(delta,time)`, not `execute`.                                                                                                  |
| `renderer.setAnimationLoop(...)` / raw `requestAnimationFrame` | The managed loop already ticks registered systems; a manual rAF does **not** run on the XR session loop, so the game won't tick in an immersive session. |

`requestAnimationFrame`/`setTimeout` are fine for pure DOM/CSS overlays (HTML fades) outside the 3D scene — but anything touching scene state, physics, scoring, or input must run in a System. The generated starter models this: see `src/index.template.ts` (`world.registerSystem(PanelSystem).registerSystem(RobotSystem)`) and `src/robot.ts` (a `createSystem` with `update()`).

**Don't let `as any` hide a broken game loop.** A "build passes, screenshot renders" app can still have a dead loop — the classic failure is guessing an engine path, casting it away, and swallowing the error into a silent rAF fallback:

```ts
// BAD — guesses a non-existent path, then silently runs a raw rAF loop
try {
  (world as any).ecs?.registerSystem?.(UpdateSystem);
} catch {
  requestAnimationFrame(rafLoop);
}
```

The correct call is `world.registerSystem(GameLoopSystem)`. Don't wrap engine calls in `try/catch` that swallows and falls back; let them throw. After `dev up`, confirm with `npx iwsdk ecs systems` that your systems are listed — if absent, the loop is running off-ECS (see `cli-reference.md`). The ECS debug tools (`pause`/`step`/`snapshot`) only see registered Systems; a hand-rolled rAF loop is invisible to them and keeps advancing even when ECS is "paused."

## ECS-Native Player Rig

```typescript
world.playerEntity; // Entity wrapping XROrigin Group
world.playerHeadEntity; // Entity for head space
world.playerSpaceEntities; // { head, raySpaces, gripSpaces, indexTipSpaces }

// Attach a HUD to the player's head
const hud = world.createTransformEntity(hudMesh, {
  parent: world.playerHeadEntity,
  persistent: true,
});
```

`createTransformEntity` returns an `Entity` whose `.object3D` is **optional** (`Object3D | undefined`). It always sets `object3D` (it falls back to `new Object3D()` when you pass nothing), so immediately after creation you can assert (`entity.object3D!.position`); inside systems/queries where an entity may have been torn down, guard instead (`if (!entity.object3D) continue;` or `entity.object3D?.position`). Do not blanket-cast to `any`.

